window.docContents[186].resolve({"/Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory/The-Pl___nnecke___Ruzsa-inequality/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory--The-Pl___nnecke___Ruzsa-inequality--Difference-Constant-Bounded-by-Square-of-Doubling-Constant":{"contents":"For a nonempty finite subset  of a commutative group, the difference constant\n() is controlled by the square of the doubling constant:\n\n\nThis is the self-paired case of the Ruzsa triangle inequality (). The\nsum-version triangle inequality with all three sets equal to  reads\n, and dividing by  yields\n.\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Additive and Combinatorial Number Theory\u0009The Plünnecke–Ruzsa inequality","header":"10.4.2. Difference Constant Bounded by Square of Doubling Constant","id":"/Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory/The-Pl___nnecke___Ruzsa-inequality/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory--The-Pl___nnecke___Ruzsa-inequality--Difference-Constant-Bounded-by-Square-of-Doubling-Constant"},"/Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory/The-polynomial-Freiman___Ruzsa-theorem/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory--The-polynomial-Freiman___Ruzsa-theorem":{"contents":"The nodes below are supplied by the public teorth/pfr project,\nwhich is sorry-free and ships its own LaTeX blueprint. They are informal here — the project builds\nagainst a different mathlib version — so they carry no (lean := …) reference; instead each records\nthe formalising declaration, an exact-source permalink at the recorded commit, and that the proof is\nsorry-free. The provenance commit is\n901bc69. These\nresults form their own component, joined to the mathlib graph through the Ruzsa covering lemma\n() and the additive cardinality bound () that the PFR\nendgame literally invokes.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Additive and Combinatorial Number Theory","header":"10.7. The polynomial Freiman–Ruzsa theorem","id":"/Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory/The-polynomial-Freiman___Ruzsa-theorem/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory--The-polynomial-Freiman___Ruzsa-theorem"},"/Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry/Weierstrass-equations-and-the-discriminant/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry--Weierstrass-equations-and-the-discriminant":{"contents":"\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Elliptic Curves and Arithmetic Geometry","header":"7.1. Weierstrass equations and the discriminant","id":"/Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry/Weierstrass-equations-and-the-discriminant/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Elliptic-Curves-and-Arithmetic-Geometry--Weierstrass-equations-and-the-discriminant"},"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project":{"contents":"The nodes below formalise results whose proofs require substantially more machinery than is in\nmathlib v4.30.0-rc2. They are drawn from the LeanModularForms project\n(https://github.com/CBirkbeck/LeanModularForms),\non its hecke-ring branch (non-default, unmerged as of June 2026), which carries the abstract Hecke\nring, the  multiplication table, eigenforms and newforms, the Atkin–Lehner old/new\ntheory, strong multiplicity one, the Shimura surjection, and the valence formula. All permalinks are\nto the fixed commit 720d950b8c31ffd69b2cc7aa5323bccaefad62e1. Each node is informal (no\n(lean := …)) and carries a provenance line recording the exact source declaration and its true\nLean status.\n\nThe development follows Shimura's Introduction to the Arithmetic Theory of Automorphic Functions,\n§3.1 and Theorem 3.24, and Miyake's Modular Forms, §4.5–4.6. Throughout this section \nis the level,  the weight, ,  the standard congruence subgroups,\n a Dirichlet character modulo ,  the cusp forms of Nebentypus , and\n,  the Hecke and diamond operators.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Modular and Automorphic Forms","header":"6.8. Results from the LeanModularForms project","id":"/Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms/Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Modular-and-Automorphic-Forms--Results-from-the-LeanModularForms-project"}});